        <h2>1. Buildertrend — Best for residential drywall subcontractors</h2>
        <p>Most custom homebuilders and residential GCs run Buildertrend. As a drywall sub, being on the same platform your GC uses is a competitive advantage. You can receive assignments, confirm scheduling, submit daily logs, and invoice through the same system — reducing friction and making you easier to work with.</p>

        <h3>Key features for drywall contractors</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Sub-facing task notifications and schedule visibility</li>
          <li>Daily log submissions with photos (drywall stages, inspection-ready shots)</li>
          <li>Change order requests that flow to the GC for approval</li>
          <li>Invoice submission through the GC's project workflow</li>
          <li>Material purchase orders with budget tracking</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>If your GC customers use Buildertrend, you should too — it makes you the easiest sub to work with.</strong></p>
          <a href="https://www.buildertrend.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn">Get Started with Buildertrend</a>
        </div>

        <h2>2. JobTread — Best for drywall job costing</h2>
        <p>JobTread gives drywall contractors real-time visibility into where each job stands financially. As material prices shift and labor hours vary, you can see committed costs and actuals against your estimate in real time — and catch margin bleed before it kills the job.</p>

        <h3>Key features</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Estimate templates for different drywall scopes (new construction vs. finish work vs. repair)</li>
          <li>Real-time budget vs. actual tracking per job</li>
          <li>Purchase orders that create committed costs automatically</li>
          <li>Change order workflow with markup tracking</li>
          <li>Reasonable $99/month starting price</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>JobTread is the right choice for drywall contractors who want to stop guessing their margins.</strong></p>
          <a href="https://www.jobtread.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn btn-outline">Try JobTread Free</a>
        </div>

        <h2>3. Contractor Foreman — Best budget all-in-one</h2>
        <p>Small drywall operations that need everything — estimates, time tracking, invoices, project tracking — without a large software budget will find Contractor Foreman delivers real value at $49/month. It's not the most polished, but it's comprehensive and affordable.</p>

        <h2>4. Procore — Best for large commercial drywall subs</h2>
        <p>Commercial drywall subcontractors working on large projects often work within Procore because their GC requires it. Procore's submittals, RFIs, and document management tools are genuinely powerful for complex commercial projects — but the platform is expensive and overkill for residential work.</p>

        <h2>5. Houzz Pro — Best for homeowner-facing drywall repair work</h2>
        <p>If you do a meaningful volume of direct-to-homeowner drywall repair, patching, and finishing work, Houzz Pro's lead generation is worth exploring. Homeowners actively search Houzz for tradespeople — and for residential drywall contractors in competitive markets, that pipeline can be valuable.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Drywall contractors serving homeowners directly: Houzz Pro's leads can fill your schedule.</strong></p>
          <a href="https://www.houzz.com/pro" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn">Try Houzz Pro</a>
        </div>

        <h2>What drywall software must handle</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Material-based takeoffs:</strong> Sheet counts, level-of-finish specifications, waste percentages</li>
          <li><strong>Phase-based scheduling:</strong> Hang, tape, finish, sand — each phase has dependencies and drying time</li>
          <li><strong>Subfloor conditions documentation:</strong> Protect yourself from framing or moisture issues you inherited</li>
          <li><strong>Real job costing:</strong> Material prices shift; you need to know your actual vs. estimated material costs per job</li>
          <li><strong>Change order capture:</strong> Extra scope in drywall — patching around rerouted plumbing, adding rooms — must be captured and billed</li>
        </ul>

